ANITA DE MONTE LAUGHS LAST â€¢ XÃ³chitl GonzÃ¡lez â€¢ #gifted @flatiron_books, @macmillan.audio & @netgalley â€¢ out 3/5

1985. A rising artist, Anita de Monte, is found dead in New York City under suspicious circumstances. By 1998, her name has been largely forgotten. But when Raquel, a third-year art history student preparing for her thesis, stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story, she questions the dynamics of her relationship that eerily mirrors the late artistâ€™s. 

Following two Latinx women in the art & academia across a decade, GonzÃ¡lez brilliantly explores the psychological burden of Brown women surviving in white-dominant spaces and their conscious/unconscious need for white validation. 

The dual timeline works well in juxtaposing Anita & Raquelâ€™s struggles and exposes how little has changed for women of color to move through institutions built to uphold white supremacy. From microaggressions and sexism to the false belief of meritocracy, my heart especially aches for all that Raquel has to endure. 

While some chapters are a little on the nose, I love the unexpected twist that portrays Anita as the ultimate unhinged woman. The sharp, sarcastic writing keeps me engaged and rooting for Anita to exact her revenge. LAST reminds me of DISORIENTATION (Elaine Hsieh Chou), YELLOWFACE (R.F. Kuang), and THE TREES (Percival Everett), and I loved every moment of it. 

The full-cast audiobook is phenomenal and captures each characterâ€™s emotions & personalities perfectly. Reading LAST is noticing the simmering rage within me threatening to boil over; I laughed, I raged, and I think you will too.

Anita De Monte Laughs Last, by Xochitl Gonzalez, is a new novel coming out March 5th. It introduces us to two women in the art world. Anita is an up-and-coming artist who is found dead. Years later, Raquel is doing her final thesis and seeks to do it on a male artist who is world famous. He just so happened to be the husband of Anita before she was found dead. Questions surrounded her death, but as the years moved on, she was forgotten. As Raquel begins to discover more about the past, her present is getting away from her, her goals and dreams finding new allies but at what consequence? As the past and present collide, will these two women get the recognition they deserve, or will the ivory walls of power descend to crush their work into oblivion?â£
â£
This is so my kind of novel. I love books set in the art world, especially when it focuses on people often perceived as outsiders. Anita and Raquel work harder than anyone but often find themselves told to be grateful for whatever scraps of acknowledgment they are given. Their fight to be heard and appreciated for their talent ignites these pages. The writing is powerful and vivid, at times funny but always with a sense of purpose. There was a point in the novel where things took a turn, and at first, I was unsure of this direction. I shouldnâ€™t have worried as Gonzalez held my hand and then demanded I shout for justice, just like her characters. I highly recommend this one.â£
â£
Thank you to @flatiron_books for the gifted copy. I will now be reading her debut novel, Olga Dies Dreaming.â£
